top_tracks.name: Plastic Beach (Feat. Mick Jones & Paul Simonon)

narrative.narrative: Your musical journey was too epic to put into words.

personality.tagline: Blessing up at 10 AM sharp like it's a 9-to-5
personality.description: You've listened to 'All Night' by Chance 183 times this year, which is basically a part-time job at this point. Your 10 AM listening peak suggests you treat workday mornings like a spiritual experience—except your church is Kendrick's discography and Chance's Coloring Book is your hymnal. You somehow burned through 22% of your entire year listening to just three artists, which is less 'eclectic taste' and more 'hip-hop monogamy.' That one day you played 'All Night' 86 times? Therapy would be cheaper. You're out here treating Gorillaz's 'Plastic Beach' like a palate cleanser between Kendrick deep-dives, and that one Dead Milkmen track in your top 10 is doing absolutely zero to convince us you're not just a golden-age hip-hop head in denial.
personality.spirit_animal: A monk who only studies three sacred texts but REALLY studies them

roasts: You played 'All Night' by Chance 183 times, and then REALLY committed by playing it 86 times in a single day. That's not appreciation, that's a cry for help.
You listened to a 1:43 interlude called 'Rich' 89 times. That's over 2.5 hours of Kendrick saying basically nothing. You good?
1,308 Kendrick plays but only 110 unique artists all year? Your Spotify Wrapped must look like a police lineup of the same five guys in different outfits.
Your listening peaked at 10 AM on a Monday in November. Either you discovered music at the worst possible time or you're using hip-hop as a coping mechanism for existing.
You managed to go entire months without logging a single song, then absolutely demolished September-November like you were trying to meet a Kendrick quota before the year ended.

aura.vibe: Conscious and uplifting, with roots deep in hip-hop's golden age
aura.description: Your aura radiates the warmth of a Sunday morning service mixed with the raw energy of West Coast backpack rap. Like Kendrick's introspection meeting Chance's joyful gospel samples, your energy flows between profound self-reflection and pure celebration. You're the person who finds spiritual meaning in a 16-bar verse and dances through life's contradictions with the wisdom of OutKast and the experimental edge of MF DOOM. Your 10 AM peak listening reveals a soul that processes the world through rhythm before noon—coffee in one hand, existential bars in the other. That 86-play day of 'All Night' wasn't obsession, it was transcendence. You don't just listen to music; you let it rewire your consciousness, one Gorillaz interlude at a time.

superlatives.reason: Played 'All Night' by Chance the Rapper 183 times—and then played it 86 times in a single day just to be sure
Peak listening at 10 AM with 704 plays—turning spreadsheets into Kendrick Lamar's greatest hits since August
Listened to 'Plastic Beach' album 245 times—environmentally conscious or just can't leave that island?

superlatives.award: Most Likely to Say 'I Listen to Real Hip-Hop'
superlatives.reason: 110 unique artists but somehow 22% of your entire year was just Kendrick Lamar (we're not judging, we get it)
Went from 12 plays in May to 974 in August—someone discovered their music library and never looked back

hot_takes: You listened to 'All Night' 86 times in ONE DAY. That's not music appreciation, that's a cry for help (or the greatest day of your life, no in-between)
22% of your entire year was just Kendrick Lamar. At this point you're not a fan, you're conducting a PhD thesis on his discography
You have 110 unique artists but spent 3,000+ minutes on Chance the Rapper's Coloring Book. We get it, you peaked emotionally in 2016
Playing a 1:43 interlude 89 times is absolutely unhinged behavior. 'Rich (interlude)' isn't even a full song—it's basically Kendrick clearing his throat
Your 10am listening sessions hit harder than most people's gym routines. 700+ plays during business hours? Someone's definitely not in meetings

suggestions: You played 'All Night' by Chance the Rapper 86 times in ONE DAY (Sept 1st). That's not listening, that's a spiritual experience. Try Noname's 'Telefone' for similar vibes when you need to loop something into oblivion.
With 85+ hours of Kendrick, 60+ hours of Chance, and 50+ hours of Ye, you're basically a Chicago-meets-Compton scholar. 2025 prediction: You'll finally admit you like J. Cole after 'discovering' him.

Your 10 AM-2 PM window is prime listening time (2,585 plays). You're either crushing it at a desk job or have the most musical morning routine ever. Try Injury Reserve or JPEGMafia to shake up those work-from-home hours.
'Redbone' as your late-night anthem (24 plays after midnight) screams introspective vibes. Dive into Steve Lacy's 'Gemini Rights' or Frank Ocean's 'Blonde' for your 2025 3 AM contemplation sessions.

Gorillaz's 'Plastic Beach' getting 245 plays shows you appreciate the weird and experimental. 2025 challenge: Explore Danny Brown's 'Atrocity Exhibition' or Injury Reserve's self-titled album—they'll scratch that genre-bending itch.
